Unstructured Data Lake Objects

Unstructured data resides in files in an external blob store, such as Amazon S3 and is referenced directly by an unstructured data lake object (UDLO).

For typical structured data, a data lake object (DLO) is a storage container for the data ingested using a data stream in Data Cloud. Unstructured data is referenced directly by a UDLO, as opposed to a data stream. By ingesting unstructured data from a given blob store into one or more UDLOs, you can organize your unstructured data files by various dimensions, such as by MIME type, business purpose, generation date, or information type. As a result, you can manage files from a single blob store through multiple UDLOs, but a single UDLO can’t span more than one blob store.

UDLO Metadata

A single UDLO contains metadata for a collection of unstructured data files.

A UDLO has these key pieces of metadata at the table level.

Content Type: For a UDLO, contains a metadata attribute value of Content
Total Records: Indicates the number of records in the UDLO. Because each record in the UDLO corresponds to a file on the blob store, the number of records in a UDLO represents the number of unstructured data files that are represented in the UDLO.
Last Updated On: The timestamp for when the file metadata stored in the UDLO was most recently modified.
Fully Qualified Keys 

Fully Qualified Keys Data Cloud adds key qualifier fields to UDLOs and UDMOs, which behave the same as in standard DLOs and DMOs. Key qualifier fields can be added when you create object relationships between DMOs and UDMOs. See Fully Qualified Keys in Data Objects.

UDLO Schema Attributes
Unstructured data lake objects (UDLOs) reference unstructured data in Data Cloud.
UDMO Schema Attributes
Unstructured data model objects (UDMOs) are groups of data created from unstructured data sources.
